06361nam a22006735i 9780804763967DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047639677 a10.1515/97808047639672doi  a(DE-B1597)581504  a(OCoLC)1312726638  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0200002bisacsh00aMaking Majorities :bConstituting the Nation in Japan, Korea, China, Malaysia, Fiji, Turkey, and the United States /ced. by Dru C. Gladney. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Issues in Asia and the Pacific00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: Making and Marking Majorities -- tPART I Japaneseness -- tI. Culturalism, Racialism, and Internationalism in the Discourse on Japanese Identity -- t2. A Conceptual Model for the Historical Relationship Between the Self and the Internal and External Others -- tPART II Koreanness -- t3. Who Speaks for Korean Shamans When Shamans Speak of the Nation? -- t4. Constructing and Deconstructing "Koreanness" -- tPART III Chineseness -- t5. On Three Definitions of Han Ren -- t6. Clashed Civilizations? -- tPART IV Malayness -- t7· Bureaucratic Management of Identity in a Modern State -- t8. Ideological Work in Constructing the Malay Majority -- tPART V Fijianness -- t9. Aspiring to Minority and Other Tactics Against Violence -- t10. When 8,870 - 850 = 1 -- tPART VI Turkishness -- t11. From Ottoman to Turk -- t12. Minority/Majority Discourse -- tPART VII Americanness -- t13. Studying Mainstreams and Minorities in North America -- t14. The Illusion of Paradise -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMajorities are made, not born. This book argues that there are no pure majorities in the Asia-Pacific region, broadly defined, nor in the West. Numerically, ethnically, politically, and culturally, societies make and mark their majorities under specific historical, political, and social circumstances. This position challenges Samuel Huntington’s influential thesis that civilizations are composed of more or less homogeneous cultures, suggesting instead that culture is as malleable as the politics that informs it. The fourteen contributors to this volume argue that emphasis on minority/majority rights is based on uncritically accepted ideas of purity, numerical superiority, and social consensus. Emphases upon multiculturalism can become ways of masking serious political, ethnic, and class differences merely in terms of cultural difference, and affirmative-action policies can isolate, identify, and stigmatize minorities as often as they homogenize, unify, and naturalize majorities. This book analyzes how minorities are made and marked across cultural, regional, and national boundaries from Hawai‘i to Turkey, a region that encompasses extraordinarily diverse populations and political developments and that is often regarded as composed of relatively homogeneous majorities. This volume details discourses of majority and minority, allowing exploration of a number of questions of more general concern in the humanities and social sciences, including: How does one become officially “ethnic” in many states in Asia? How are understandings of majority and minority cultures created and shaped in specific political and historical contexts? How does the state shape the way people think of themselves? How do people resist, transform, and appropriate these official representations?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aA. B., Shamsul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeringil, Selim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladney, Dru C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladney, Dru C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHae-joang, Cho, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandler, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendall, Laurel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirişci, Kemal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilner, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhnuki-Tierney, Emiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOkamura, Jonathan Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShih-chung, Hsieh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoshino, Kosaku, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107042110 cprintz978080473047140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476396740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804763967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804763967/original  a978-3-11-070421-1  Stanford University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles